x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">On Wednesday, to no=
 one=E2=80=99s surprise, National Basketball Association Commissioner <b>Ad=
am Silver </b>formally rejected <b>David Zaslav</b>=E2=80=99s attempt to ex=
ercise Warner Bros. Discovery=E2=80=99s matching rights for a package of ga=
mes that had been claimed by Amazon. Minutes later, the league announced th=
at it would proceed with its deals with Amazon, Disney, and NBCUniversal=E2=
=80=94a $77 billion win for the NBA over 11 years=E2=80=94while WBD=E2=80=
=99s lawyers began finalizing a breach-of-contract lawsuit they would event=
ually file on Friday. The insider consensus was that Zaz=E2=80=99s failure =
to keep the NBA on TNT was yet another example of hapless mismanagement, an=
d his decision to sue the league would only make matters worse. What better=
 way to appeal to other potential partners than signaling that, in addition=
 to being saddled with debt and tethered to a declining
linear business, you can also be a litigious sore loser?<br/><br/>Shortly a=
fter the NBA=E2=80=99s announcement, however, civil rights leaders, influen=
tial Black public figures, and some of the league=E2=80=99s current and for=
mer players got pitched on a different narrative. Over the last 48 hours, r=
epresentatives from Edelman, the white shoe P.R. firm, have called and text=
ed these people on behalf of WBD, seeking to persuade them that the NBA=E2=
=80=99s decision to side with a streaming service instead of a linear partn=
er, like TNT, will disenfranchise Black and other minority viewers. =E2=80=
=9CWho=E2=80=99s thinking about Uncle Bob?=E2=80=9D one Edelman rep wrote i=
n one text. =E2=80=9CNearly half of TNT viewers are Black. 2 in 5 NBA fans =
are non-white. 42 million rural Americans lack access to reliable high-spee=
d internet=E2=80=94and for millions more in America=E2=80=99s cities and su=
burbs, it=E2=80=99s available but too costly.=E2=80=9D <br/></td>
